law.text:
The military judge or officer presiding over a court-martial may:
issue a warrant to arrest and bring before the court for trial an accused individual who has received a copy of the charge and an order to appear and who fails to appear before the court-martial;
issue a subpoena to attend, give testimony, or produce documents or other tangible things;
enforce by attachment the attendance of witnesses and the production of documents and other tangible things; and
impose a sentence for a refusal to be sworn or to answer as provided in actions before civil courts.
